      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prostate-Cancer Ad</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Terry Roe letter, commenting on August 26 article, deplores PETA's milk-mustache ad of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani linking his prostate cancer to drinking milk; says mocking human suffering in furtherance of animal rights is cruel and misguided</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a survivor of metastatic prostate cancer, I recoiled from PETA's milk-mustache ad of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani (''Giuliani Threatens Suit Over Ads Featuring Him,'' news article, Aug. 26).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a survivor of metastatic prostate cancer, I recoiled from PETA's milk-mustache ad of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani (''Giuliani Threatens Suit Over Ads Featuring Him,'' news article, Aug. 26).</p>
        <p>The attempt at humor with the lighthearted headline ''Got prostate cancer?'' is distressing, certainly to the 180,000 men so diagnosed this year. Even those men who are ''cured'' will to some degree experience erectile dysfunction, incontinence and possibly depression. Those who die will do so in the agony of resulting bone cancer. To mock such human suffering in the furtherance of animal rights is cruel and misguided.</p>
        <p>TERRY ROE  Martinsville, N.J., Aug. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is vice chairman of Us Too International, prostate cancer survivor support groups.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
